, Slaidburn, West Yorkshire, England":"Slaidburn, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1287–about 1308":"circa 1287–circa 1308","1254–1316":"1254–1316","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1287–1308":"1287–1308","1316":"1316","about 1308":"circa 1308","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1254":"1254","about 1287":"circa 1287","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England","Hamerton Hall, Slaidburn, West Yorkshire, England":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England"},"en":{"about 1287–about 1308":"about 1287–about 1308","1254–1316":"1254–1316","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1287–1308":"1287–1308","1316":"1316","about 1308":"about 1308","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1254":"1254","about 1287":"about 1287","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England","Hamerton Hall, Slaidburn, West Yorkshire, England":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Wigglesworth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): habitational name from Wigglesworth in North Yorkshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Winchelesuuorde</i>, from the genitive case of the Old English byname <i>Wincel</i> meaning ‘child’ + Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure’.","History: Michael Wigglesworth (1631–1705), Puritan poet and preacher, was brought from Yorkshire to New England as a child in 1638. His first home was in Charlestown, MA; subsequently, he settled in New Haven, CT. From 1651 onward he was a fellow of Harvard College; in 1654 he was appointed minister at Malden, MA. His son and grandson, both named Edward were professors of divinity at Harvard."],"variants":[{"name":"Wiglesworth","meanings":["English: variant of   Wigglesworth  ."]},{"name":"Wrigglesworth","meanings":["English: habitational name from Woodlesford in Oulton (Yorkshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>wrīdels</i> ‘thicket’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. There has been much confusion with   Wigglesworth  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":3,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan of Wigglesworth was born about 1287, in Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England. She married Stephen de Hamerton. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1308, in Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England, at the age of 23."},"et":{"about 1287–about 1308":"umbes 1287–umbes 1308","1254–1316":"1254–1316","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1287–1308":"1287–1308","1316":"1316","about 1308":"umbes 1308","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1254":"1254","about 1287":"umbes 1287","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England","Hamerton Hall, Slaidburn, West Yorkshire, England":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1287–about 1308":"noin 1287–noin 1308","1254–1316":"1254–1316","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1287–1308":"1287–1308","1316":"1316","about 1308":"noin 1308","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1254":"1254","about 1287":"noin 1287","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England","Hamerton Hall, Slaidburn, West Yorkshire, England":"Slaidburn, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England":"Hamerton, Huntingdonshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1287–about 1308":"environ 1287–environ 1308","1254–1316":"1254–1316","1308–1334":"1308–1334","1287–1308":"1287–1308","1316":"1316","about 1308":"environ 1308","1334":"1334","1287":"1287","1254":"1254","about 1287":"environ 1287","1308":"1308","1290":"1290","Wigglesworth, Yorkshire, England":"Wigglesworth, Everwyck, 